    "summary": "Iberian Culture (c. 500–200 BC) was the pre-Roman civilization of the eastern and southeastern Iberian Peninsula, characterized by developed urban life, a distinct artistic tradition, an indigenous script, extensive trade contacts with Phoenicians, Greeks, and Carthaginians, and the fierce warrior culture that made the peninsula so difficult for Rome to pacify during the [[event:1093|Roman Conquest of Hispania]].\n\nThe Iberians were not a unified people but a collection of related cultures sharing language, artistic styles, and material culture along the Mediterranean coast of Spain. Iberian cities had stone fortifications, specialized craft production (fine pottery, bronze work), and participation in Mediterranean trade networks. Iberian script, adapted from Phoenician or Greek models, remains partially undeciphered — enough is readable to identify personal names and commercial records, but the language's linguistic affinities remain debated. Iberian warriors — slingers, javelin-throwers, and skilled cavalry — were recruited as mercenaries across the Mediterranean including by Carthage; Hannibal's army that crossed the Alps in [[event:1055|Hannibal's Crossing of the Alps]] included substantial Iberian contingents. Roman conquest beginning in 218 BC gradually Latinized the region, but the process took nearly two centuries and involved ferocious resistance, as in the [[event:1224|Numantine War]].",
